<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100694277938297></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100694277938297><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=6&mid=100694277938297>RE: LD problems</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=6&mid=100694277938297#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=83710><span id=Scholar>jcasetnl</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>147 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, Nov 28th 5:19 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[4.70]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I have dwealt in that cave my friend.<br><br>When I first started playing EQ I was traveling extensively for my job, nearly 40 weeks/year.&nbsp;&nbsp;I had a company laptop.  It was a P3 800 with 8 megs of onboard video, no slouch by any means.  It was fully capable of displaying EQ as well as it could be displayed but...<br><br>Frequently I had situations where the framerate would drop to nothing (yes, particle effects were off).  I could barely move the mouse and if I used the arrow keys to look around I would start spinning uncontrollably.  Even typing would be delayed for several seconds.  I thought this was a lag problem but it wasn't.  Even if your connection is garbage, your framerate should not be affected much.  If you experience this, most likely you have audio, video, modem or more than one of these built onto the motherboard.  In this type of setup, these components draw off your main CPU.  This is a typical setup in a business class machine.<br><br>In addition, I experienced a lot of lag and frequent disconnects, but not as bad as what you're talking about.  <br><br>So one thing you may want to look into is whether or not any of the three components above are built into the motherboard.  <br><br>A problem I frequently have now is my ISP sucks.  I use AT+T/IBM Global Internet Access.  It's free, which is why I still use it.  This ISP is geared toward businesses and handles mostly business accounts.  It is awful for gaming.  Frequently my connection will still be active, but some other network layer component will fail, such as DNS or even TCP/IP altogether.  In other words, I still maintain a PPP connection but that's it.  If you didn't follow that, don't worry about it.  What it basically means is that it appears that everything is alright but my connection is essentially down.  If I wait a minute or two it will ussually be fine again.  But a minute of connection loss in EQ means a LD.  In my case, I have four different locations I can dial into locally.  So even when one gets really flaky, I can just dial into another.  If there is another local dialup, you might try that one to see if it is more stable.  It might point to a problem with your ISP.  Along these same lines, you might pick up a free AOL cd and use it for a few days on the free hours.  See if you can duplicate the problem.  If you have the same problem, it's likely a problem with your computer.  If the connection problems seem to go away, then it's likely your ISP.<br><br>I still frequently get the garbled connection bar you're referring to and at least 50% it will result in a LD.  <br><br>Unfortunately with connection problems there are a few factors involved.  But if you take a look into the above stuff and get back to the board, I might be able to help.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
